<paragraph blockId="4.[191,1440,993,1187]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
The most similar taxon with respect to the clypeus, antennal form, and claws is the South American tanyproctine genus 
<emphasis box="[315,435,1027,1052]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Luispenaia</emphasis>
Martínez (
<bibRefCitation author="Mondaca J &amp; Pizarro-Araya J &amp; Alfaro FM" box="[557,790,1026,1053]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="549 - 562" refId="ref3531" refString="Mondaca J, Pizarro-Araya J, Alfaro FM. 2019. Revision of the genus Luispenaia Martinez (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Melolonthinae: Tanyproctini), with description of three new species from the Atacama Desert, Chile. Zootaxa 4615 (3): 549 - 562." type="journal article" year="2019">Mondaca et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
), however, species of that genus possess a distinct labrum, mandibles, and protibial spurs. In the key to tribes of Nearctic 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1819" box="[885,1049,1060,1086]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Melolonthinae">Melolonthinae</taxonomicName>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="Evans AV &amp; Smith ABT" box="[1083,1351,1060,1087]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="51 - 77" refId="ref3388" refString="Evans AV, Smith ABT. 2020. On the tribal classification of the Nearctic Melolonthinae (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae), with descriptions of new species of Acoma Casey, 1889. Zootaxa 4748 (1): 51 - 77." type="journal article" year="2020">Evans and Smith (2020)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Paulsen" authorityYear="2021" box="[1360,1440,1060,1086]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Ardella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1360,1440,1060,1086]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Ardella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
will key to Phobetusini in couplet 9, however it differs significantly from 
<emphasis box="[1008,1108,1094,1120]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Phobetus</emphasis>
LeConte in lacking a labrum, protibial spur, and sternal spiracles. The proximal position of the metatibial spurs in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Paulsen" authorityYear="2021" box="[1124,1204,1127,1153]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Ardella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1124,1204,1127,1153]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Ardella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
such that they barely reach the metatibial apex appears to be unique among all taxa studied.
</paragraph>
